{"title_page": "C. R. Evers & Co.", "text_new": "[[File:C. R. Evers & Co.jpg|thumb|The Zinn family's music room]]\n'''C. R. Evers & Co.''' was a [[Denmark|Danish]] confectionary company based in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The '''Evers''' brand is now owned by [[Carletti]].\n\n==History==\n\nC.R. Evers & Co. was founded by Christian Rudolph Evers (1821-1877) in 1867.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=Zy6RDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=C.+R.+Evers+%26+Co.+1867&source=bl&ots=MbHFBspIif&sig=ACfU3U27XSqOJVyKFEw52eGInXyzH0rcQQ&hl=da&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjV2aueturoAhUM3qQKHZVDBAoQ6AEwAHoECAoQLQ#v=onepage&q=C.%20R.%20Evers%20%26%20Co.%201867&f=false|title=Blikskilte: Danske reklameskilte|language=Danish|author=Tommy Richard Fogh Andersen|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Ge had been educated as a pharmacist in 1843 but had later worked first as a merchant in [[Vejle]] and then as a brewer and manufacturer of candles in [[Ribe, Denmark|Ribe]]. In 1984 he was granted a royal monopoly on the production of a malt extract of his own invention. The malt extract came in a small [[tin box]] and was used for a preparation of a \"tasty, potent beer-like drink\". He was that same year also granted a patent on the malt extract in Sweden, Belgium, France, Austria and Hungary. The name C.R. Evers & Co. was adopted when the cost of obtaining these patents forced him to enter into a partnership with other investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dfhf.dk/~dfhf5979/media/pdf/e-artikel2.pdf|title=De mindre og n\u00e6sten glemte l\u00e6gemiddelindustrivirksomheder|language=Danish|author=J\u00f8rgen V. Grevsen, Hanne Kirkegaard, Edith Kruse & Poul R. Kruse|publisher=Theriaca|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEvers' widow continued the company after his death in 1877. She completed a new factory on Peder Skrams Gade in Copenhagen's new [[Gammelholm]] neighbourhood.\n\nHelmuth Brix acquired the company in 1886. He inaugurated a new factory at [[Fasanvej|\u00d8stre Fasanvej]] 15 (now [[Fasanvej|Nordre Fasanvej]] 101) in 1896. ''{{Illustreret Tidende]]'' brought an article about the company in connection with its 40 years aniverasary\n\nThe company was in 1924 acquired by  A. Fredsted (born 1887) and C. Fjeldborg (born 1879).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF100-199/Side%20155%20Esma%20-%20Expr.html|title=G. Halkier & Co.|language=Danish|website=coneliand.dk|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  The company was later in the century subject to a number of mergers and disappeared in the 1990s. The Evers brand is now owned hy [[Carletti]].\n\n==Cultural references==\nIn [[Hans Scherfig]]'s ''[[Stolen Spring]]'', it is a poisoned Evers Melt Drop that causes the sudden death of C. Blomme in [[Hans Scherfig]]'s ''[[Stolen Spring]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://carletti.dk/Bolcher-1009.aspx Official website]\n* [http://www.kimbj.dk/index.asp?loadContent=154773 C. R. Evers & Co.  beer labels]\n* [http://www.troldkaer-katteri.dk/brixaner.html Helmuth Brix]\n\n[[Category:Danish confectionery]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1867]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:C. R. Evers & Co.jpg|thumb|The Zinn family's music room]]\n'''C. R. Evers & Co.''' was a [[Denmark|Danish]] confectionary company based in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The '''Evers''' brand is now owned by [[Carletti]].\n\n==History==\n\nC.R. Evers & Co. was founded by Christian Rudolph Evers (1821-1877) in 1867.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=Zy6RDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=C.+R.+Evers+%26+Co.+1867&source=bl&ots=MbHFBspIif&sig=ACfU3U27XSqOJVyKFEw52eGInXyzH0rcQQ&hl=da&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjV2aueturoAhUM3qQKHZVDBAoQ6AEwAHoECAoQLQ#v=onepage&q=C.%20R.%20Evers%20%26%20Co.%201867&f=false|title=Blikskilte: Danske reklameskilte|language=Danish|author=Tommy Richard Fogh Andersen|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Ge had been educated as a pharmacist in 1843 but had later worked first as a merchant in [[Vejle]] and then as a brewer and manufacturer of candles in [[Ribe, Denmark|Ribe]]. In 1984 he was granted a royal monopoly on the production of a malt extract of his own invention. The malt extract came in a small [[tin box]] and was used for a preparation of a \"tasty, potent beer-like drink\". He was that same year also granted a patent on the malt extract in Sweden, Belgium, France, Austria and Hungary. The name C.R. Evers & Co. was adopted when the cost of obtaining these patents forced him to enter into a partnership with other investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dfhf.dk/~dfhf5979/media/pdf/e-artikel2.pdf|title=De mindre og n\u00e6sten glemte l\u00e6gemiddelindustrivirksomheder|language=Danish|author=J\u00f8rgen V. Grevsen, Hanne Kirkegaard, Edith Kruse & Poul R. Kruse|publisher=Theriaca|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nEvers' widow continued the company after his death in 1877. She completed a new factory on Peder Skrams Gade in Copenhagen's new [[Gammelholm]] neighbourhood.\n\nHelmuth Brix acquired the company in 1886. He inaugurated a new factory at [[Fasanvej|\u00d8stre Fasanvej]] 15 (now [[Fasanvej|Nordre Fasanvej]] 101) in 1896. ''{{Illustreret Tidende]]'' brought an article about the company in connection with its 40 years aniverasary\n\nThe company was in 1924 acquired by  A. Fredsted (born 1887) and C. Fjeldborg (born 1879).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF100-199/Side%20155%20Esma%20-%20Expr.html|title=G. Halkier & Co.|language=Danish|website=coneliand.dk|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  The company was later in the century subject to a number of mergers and disappeared in the 1990s. The Evers brand is now owned hy [[Carletti]].\n\n==Cultural references==\nIn [[Hans Scherfig]]'s ''[[Stolen Spring]]'', it is a poisoned Evers Melt Drop that causes the sudden death of C. Blomme in [[Hans Scherfig]]'s ''[[Stolen Spring]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Ex